  <body>
    <segment id="1">
Incomprehensible argument about religion</segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="34" relname="preparation">

A colleague recently said:</segment>
    <segment id="16" parent="34" relname="span">

&quot;Fortunately this is no longer a problem at our school!</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="16" relname="cause">  

Our students can freely choose between LER [Lebensgestaltung-Ethik-Religionskunde] and religion.&quot;</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="17" relname="preparation"> 

Unfortunately I had to prove her wrong:</segment>
    <segment id="17" parent="33" relname="span">  

The legislature is lagging far behind this reality.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="37" relname="interpretation">  

And now even our state government seems determined to finally eliminate this (apparent!) equal treatment of the two subjects.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="5" relname="concession">  

Stolpe, Reiche &amp; Co. say yes to a possible compromise offer from Karlsruhe,</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="37" relname="span"> 

but decree: There cannot be a mandatory area of LER/Religion in elections.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="38" relname="joint">  

Who still understands the debate and the underlying interests?</segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="38" relname="joint">

The school policy in Brandenburg seems to have turned into a playground for politicians seeking recognition.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="25" relname="span">  

Instead of ensuring a solidly financed, long-term education policy,</segment>
    <segment id="18" parent="24" relname="conjunction"> 

that allows for quiet work,</segment>
    <segment id="19" parent="24" relname="conjunction"> 

and is oriented towards needs,</segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="26" relname="span"> 

a hectic reaction is made to every trend:</segment>
    <segment id="20" parent="13" relname="e-elaboration"> 

media offensives, fast-track classes, centralized final exams ...</segment>
    <segment id="21" parent="27" relname="interpretation"> 

There is no waiting for democratic processes from below.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="31" relname="circumstance">

The teachers and students suffer.</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="22" relname="purpose">  

LER and religion teachers have made personal commitment to further their training </segment>
    <segment id="22" parent="29" relname="span"> 

in order to be able to teach their subject - </segment>
    <segment id="23" parent="30" relname="span"> 

and the government is postponing the recognition of a practice that has proven successful.</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="23" relname="reason">  

It must be assumed that they have no interest in the involvement of the church in schools.</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="31" relname="span"> 

It should welcome everyone who is willing to provide qualified cooperation in this problem area of ​​our society.</segment>
